rs of fieldwork in web newsrooms in the United States and France, including more than one hundred interviews with journalists, Christin reveals many similarities among the media groups examined—their editorial goals, technological tools, and even office furniture. Yet she uncovers crucial and paradoxical differences in how American and French journalists understand audience analytics and how these affect the news produced in each country. American journalists routinely disregard traffic numbers and primarily rely on the opinion of their peers to define journalistic quality. Meanwhile, French journalists fixate on internet traffic and view these numbers as a sign of their resonance in the public sphere. Christin offers cultural and historical explanations for these disparities, arguing that distinct journalistic traditions structure how journalists make sense of digital measurements in the two countries.Contrary to the popular belief that analytics and algorithms are globally homogenizing forces, Metrics at Work shows that computational technologies can have surprisingly divergent ramifications for work and organizations worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aJournalismxTechnological innovationszFrance. 0aJournalismxTechnological innovationszUnited States. 0aWeb usage mining in journalismzFrance. 0aWeb usage mining in journalismzUnited States. 0aWeb usage mining in journalism-United States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAlgorithmic Power and Politics.  aAutomating the News.  aCaitlin Petre.  aCathy O’Neil.  aClayton Childress.  aDesperate Measures.  aEugenia Mitchelstein.  aLaPlace.  aNancy Baym.  aNicholas Diakopoulos.  aPablo Boczkowski.  aPlaying to the Crowd.  aTaina Bucher.  aThe News Gap.  aTheNotebook.  aUnder the Cover.  aWeapons of Math Destruc